County Level Relationships Between Poverty and Adverse Health Conditions

Author

Breanna Post, Asmaa Elsayed, Nailah Gayle

Published

February 18, 2026

Introduction:

For our group project, we wanted to see if places that have more barriers to getting healthy food also tend to have worse health outcomes. At first we were trying to measure food deserts, but it ended up being kinda hard to make one clean county-level food desert variable that matched well with our health data. The usda data is super detailed at the census tract level, but the cdc places data we used is county level, and it only had the measures we needed in 2023. So to keep the join simple and not make too many assumptions, we focused this deliverable on something more consistent: county level poverty from the usda data (summarized up from tracts) and county level health outcomes from cdc places (obesity and diabetes). This lets us start by looking for basic patterns between poverty and these outcomes, and it gives us a solid joined dataset we can build on for the later parts of the project.

Section I: USDA census

I.1 Data source:

Dataset: USDA Economic Research Service (ERS) Food Access Research Atlas (2019 release).

Link: https://www.ers.usda.gov/data-products/food-access-research-atlas

Our first dataset comes from the USDA food access research atlas in 2019. It is a public federal dataset that measures food access and related census-tract conditions across the United States, including poverty, income, vehicle access, and low-income or low-access indicators.

I.2 Data meaning

This dataset shows census-tract level conditions that can make it easier or harder for people to access healthy food. It matters for our project because food access, along with factors like income and vehicle access, can connect to health outcomes like obesity and diabetes, which we will pull from our second dataset

Section 2: CDC places

II.1 Data Source

Link: https://www.cdc.gov/places/

Our second dataset comes from the CDC PLACES program. It is a public health dataset that provides county-level estimates for many health measures across the United States, based on BRFSS survey data and CDC modeling methods. We are using it because it includes outcomes like obesity and diagnosed diabetes that we can compare with food access indicators from the USDA dataset.

II.2 Data meaning

This dataset provides county level estimates for health outcomes and risk factors, reported as percentages for specific measures. It matters for our project because it includes outcomes like obesity and diagnosed diabetes, which we can compare with food access and socioeconomic indicators from the USDA dataset to look for patterns between access to healthy food and health at the local level.

II.4 Data Join

The join will use a county ID. In cdc_places, the county code is LocationID. In the USDA data, the main ID is CensusTract, so it does not match LocationID exactly. CensusTract is an 11 digit code, where the first 2 digits are the state, the next 3 digits are the county, and the last 6 digits are the tract, and LocationID is the same except without the 6 digit tract code. Because of that, we can take the first 5 digits of CensusTract to get the county code, then join that to LocationID. We will use a left_join so we keep all USDA rows and only add PLACES values when they exist..

The cdc_places dataset is not ready to join as-is because it includes many different health measures and more than one year. Section 3: Joining

III.1 Changes

Before joining, we made a few changes so the two datasets would work together. We kept CensusTract as a character column so it keeps leading zeros, and we cleaned MedianFamilyIncome by turning null into na and converting it to numeric. Because the USDA data is tract level and the places file is county level, we created a new county_ID by taking the first five digits of CensusTract. We then summarized the USDA tract data up to the county level. For the PLACES data, we filtered to the year 2023 and only kept the two measures we care about, obesity and diabetes . We also filtered to one value type so we would not get duplicate values when we reshaped the data. Finally, we pivoted places from long format to wide format so each county appears once with obesity and diabetes as columns.

III.2 Prepare USDA for join

Make county_ID from only keeping the first 5 digits of CensusTract

usda_county <- usda_clean |>
  mutate(
    county_ID = str_sub(CensusTract, 1, 5)
  )

Get the averages of each poverty indicator in usda_county

usda_county_summary <- usda_county |>
  group_by(county_ID) |>
  summarize(
    tracts = n(),
    avg_poverty = mean(PovertyRate, na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_income = mean(MedianFamilyIncome, na.rm = TRUE),
    pct_low_income_tracts = mean(LowIncomeTracts, na.rm = TRUE) * 100,
    pct_lila_1and10 = mean(LILATracts_1And10, na.rm = TRUE) * 100,
    pct_lila_vehicle = mean(LILATracts_Vehicle, na.rm = TRUE) * 100,
    .groups = "drop"
  )

The USDA dataset is at the census tract level, but our CDC dataset is at the county level, so we cannot join them directly. To fix this, we created county_ID from CensusTract by taking the first five digits, which represent the county code. Then we grouped by county_ID and summarized the USDA variables so we have one row per county. This gives us county level averages and percentages that we can compare to county health outcomes in CDC.

III.6 Codebooks / column documentation links

  • USDA Food Access Research Atlas variable list (codebook PDF): https://www.ers.usda.gov/sites/default/files/images/variablelist_gc.pdf

  • CDC PLACES data dictionary: https://data.cdc.gov/500-Cities-Places/PLACES-and-500-Cities-Data-Dictionary/m35w-spkz

The most important variables we plan to use:

  • obesity (CDC PLACES): adult obesity prevalence estimate (percent)

  • diabetes (CDC PLACES): diagnosed diabetes prevalence estimate (percent)

  • avg_poverty (USDA): average tract poverty rate, summarized to county level

  • avg_income (USDA): average median family income, summarized to county level

  • pct_low_income_tracts (USDA): percent of tracts flagged as low income inside a county

III.7 Data Bias

Our combined dataset has a few limits that could create bias. The USDA data starts at the census tract level, but we summarized it to the county level, which can hide differences inside a county. For example, some tracts might have much higher poverty , but the county average smooths that out and we can miss those pockets. The PLACES numbers are also estimates made from survey data and modeling, not direct medical records, so thereâs some uncertainty. A small number of counties are missing values too. Also, the timing doesnât line up perfectly: the USDA Food Access dataset we used is a 2019 release, while the CDC PLACES data we used is from 2023. Between those years, COVID-19 changed a lot, like jobs, income, and health behaviors, and many places saw higher prices and economic stress. Because of that, some counties could look âmismatchedâ since weâre comparing older conditions with newer health estimates, so this is more exploratory and not a perfect match.

For human rights principles, privacy risk is low because the data is aggregated, so no personal names or addresses. Accountability and transparency come from clearly explaining where the data came from and what we did to clean and join it. Fairness and nondiscrimination are still concerns because missing context or averaging can hide differences for some groups. Human control of technology and professional responsibility matter because we should not treat these patterns like they prove cause and effect. Promotion of human values means using the results to understand barriers and support healthier communities, not to place blame people or counties or use that data for things like pricing health insurance.

IV.3 Create poverty groups

We created poverty groups to make it easier to compare patterns across low, mid, and high poverty counties.

joined_health <- joined_health |>
  mutate(
    poverty_group = case_when(
      avg_poverty >= 20 ~ "High poverty (20%+)",
      avg_poverty >= 10 ~ "Mid poverty (10-19.9%)",
      TRUE ~ "Lower poverty (<10%)"
    ))
